\section{Vision Node}

The vision node operates on the RGB-image and the depth-registered point cloud from the main RGBD-camera. The output are two messages. The VisionResult message sent to the mapping node and the \llplanner node contains the results of the room type classification and the object detection and is described in listing \ref{VisionResult}. The HighConfidenceObjects message sent only to the \llplanner contains the types and locations of object detections with very high confidence and is described in listing \ref{HighConfidenceObjects}.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=vision/VisionResult,frame=single, label=VisionResult]
   Header header
   DetectionSample[] samples
      geometry_msgs/Point position
      float32[] probabilities 
   float32[] room_type_probabilities
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,caption=vision/HighConfidenceObjects,frame=single,label=HighConfidenceObjects]
   Header header
   geometry_msgs/Point[] positions
   int16[] object_types
\end{lstlisting} 

The implementation of this node uses two threads. The first thread waits for input images and point clouds and decides if an images should be processed. The second thread runs the CNNs on the images delivered by the first thread, creates the output messages and publishes these messages. The multi-threaded approach is used to avoid waiting for a new image and to be able to receive images all the time.  

The decision to process an image is made base on the movement of the robot. If the robot turns too fast the images are blurry and have to be discarded. If the robot does not move no new information is gathered and no processing is necessary. This also avoid using the same information multiple times in the mapping. The movement of the robot is obtained from the odometry data, which is accessible through the tf library. If an image should be processed the image and the current point cloud are put into a buffer for the second thread.

The processing of an image is done in three steps, executing the place classification CNN, executing the the object detection CNN and the creation of the output messages using the results of the CNNs. In the following these steps are described in more detail. 

\subsection{Place Classification}

In this thesis a CNN using the VGGNet-16 model and trained on the Places205 dataset is used. The training was done by Wang et al. described in []. %TODO: referenz
This CNN was chosen as it achieves state-of-the-art performance with a top1 accuracy of about 60\% on the Place205 testset. The second reason is that the model of the CNN and the trained weights are publicly available and ready to use with the Caffe deep learning library. Caffe %TODO referenz
is an open-source deep-learning framework written in C++. Using CUDA the CNN can be executed on the GPU, which is essential for running large neural networks at reasonable frame rates. On the used hardware a forward pass takes about 30\,ms. 

An example code for setting up a CNN and executing classifications using Caffe is available. This code was modified to use the chosen CNN and adapted to fit into the vision node. The result of the classification executed on an image is an array of 205 probability values, one for each place category.

\subsection{Object Detection} 

For object detection the YOLOv3 object detection CNN is used. This CNN was chosen because according to its publication it has the best trade-off between speed and accuracy. State-of-the-art object detection systems cannot be used because the used GPU is not fast enough to achieve reasonable frame rates. With YOLOv3 a forward pass still takes about 150\,ms. YOLOv3 is available running on a second deep learning framework, which is Darknet. Darknet is an open-source, written in C and also uses CUDA for GPU support. This causes problems when linking as Caffe links CUDA with C++-linkage and Darknet with C-linkage. To resolve this problem Darknet was ported to C++, which involved mainly renaming of variables to names valid in C++. The code of an example program using YOLOv3 is shipped with Darknet, which includes the post-processing of the result of the CNN. This code was adapted and integrated into the vision node code. The main adaptation was to change the input size to 640x480, which is the resolution of the RGBD-camera. 

The output is an array of object detections. Each objects consists of a bounding box, given by the location of the center and the size in pixels, and an array of probabilities, one probability for every object class. 

\subsection{Output Generation}

The VisionResult message should only contain the probabilities of the relevant indoor place categories, also called room types. Using an array containing information about what place categories are relevant all irrelevant place categories are removed from the result of the place classification. The remaining probabilities are set to one and the resulting array is inserted into the VisionResult message.

An iteration is done over the array of object detections. If the probability of the most likely object class of a detection is lower than a threshold value, which is set to 0.00001, the detection is discarded. If the probability of the most likely object class of a detection is higher than a second threshold, which is set to 0.9, the detection is assumed to be correct. In this case the median distance to camera of all points in the bounding box is calculated. Using this distance the center of the bounding box is projected into 3D space and this point is assumed to be the object location. This object location and the id of the 

The samples in the VisionResult are randomly drawn from the image. If the point corresponding to the pixel is not valid, another sample is drawn instead. 
